For those not warring, or those wanting a change of pace, let's get quizzical

Quiz #1: odd one out
You have 12 cubes - 11 of them are identical (size, color, weight, texture, etc.). The 12th is different from the rest only in weight (may be heavier OR lighter).

The only way you can measure the cubes is through a standard balance scale, which can hold any number of cubes on either side. You can keep track of which cube is which between measurements (e.g., assume that they're numbered 1-12, and that the numbering doesn't effect the weight).

In three measurements, how can you identify the odd cube out? Can you also, from those same measurements, tell whether it is heavier or lighter than the others?

I look forward to seeing the clever solutions

On june 6, 2010
WerWolf
Lazy Mamba

And who said it would be a heavy Cup ?! xD
It could also be a really light one

So, the answer:

Number them from 1 to 12.

Make 3 Groups (1-4 / 5-8 / 9-12)

Weigh 1,2,3,4 vs 5,6,7,8 with 3 possible outcomes:

1. They are balanced = 9-12 have the odd cup, so weigh 6,7,8 vs 9,10,11 with 3 possible outcomes:

If 6,7,8 vs 9,10,11 is balanced, 12 is the odd cup. Weigh it with another cup to determine if heavier or lighter.
If 9,10,11 is heavier then they contain a heavy cup. Weigh 9 vs 10, if balanced then 11 is the heavier cup, else the heavier of 9 or 10 is the heavy cup.
If 9,10,11 is lighter, they include a light cup. Weigh 9 vs 10, if balanced then 11 is the light cup, else the lighter one of 9 or 10 is the light cup.

2. If 5,6,7,8 > 1,2,3,4 then either 5,6,7,8 contains a heavy cup or 1,2,3,4 contains a light cup so weigh 1,2,5 vs 3,6,12 with 3 possible outcomes:

If 1,2,5 vs 3,6,12 balances, then either 4 is the light cup or 7 or 8 is a heavy cup. Weigh 7 vs 8, if they balance then 4 is the light cup, or the heaviest of 7 vs 8 is the heavy cup.
If 3,6,12 is heavier then either 6 is the heavy cup or 1 or 2 is a light cup. Weigh 1 vs 2, if balanced then 6 is the heavy cup, or the lighter of 1 vs 2 is a light cup.
If 3,6,12 is light then either 3 is light or 5 is heavy. Weigh 3 against another cup, if balanced then 5 is the heavy cup else 3 is the light cup.

3. If 1,2,3,4 > 5,6,7,8 then either 1,2,3,4 contains a heavy cup or 5,6,7,8 contains a light cup so weigh 5,6,1 vs 7,2,12 with 3 possible outcomes:

If 5,6,1 vs 7,2,12 is balanced, then either 8 is the light cup or 3 or 4 is a heavy cup. Weigh 3 vs 4, if balanced then 8 is the light cup, or the heavier of 3 vs 4 is the heavy cup.
If 7,2,12 is heavier then either 2 is the heavy cup or 5 or 6 is a light cup. Weigh 5 vs 6, if balanced then 2 is the heavy cup, or the lighter of 5 vs 6 is the light cup.
If 7,2,12 is light then either 7 is light or 1 is heavy. Weigh 7 against any other cup, if balanced then 1 is the heavy cup else 7 is the light cup.

So you get to know which cup is heavier OR lighter than the other 11 ^^

I was fishing pirhan-os by the river Styx when I saw the old and not always so merry ferryman Charon come down the river on his boat. Much to my astonishment, the boat was loaded with something out of the ordinary: a fine looking barrel. I asked where Charon had found it and he just grunted and pointed to the river. At least Charon was his usual silent self.

I was eager to study the barrel more closely but I noticed Charon was holding out his hand and piercing me with that fierce gaze of his. Ah yes, nothing is free in life (or afterlife for that matter!). I gave the old man an obol as a payment for bringing the barrel to me and I think I saw a hint of fleeting smile on his bearded face. Could be I was mistaken.

Business concluded, I turned towards the barrel and noticed a golden plate on its side. The plate read: "May this sign of goodwill end up in the right hands". There was also the official seal of Voodoo and an inscription "The Very Finest Special Grog".

"What a wonderful thing they have sent to us", I thought to myself and turned to Charon, intending to ask if he'd like to taste this exquisite treat. The ancient boatman was nowhere to be seen and a dense mist had shrouded the river. The antics of Charon... I shrugged my shoulders, took a hold of the barrel and fishing rod and started my trek back to the castle.

At the castle, the barrel was quickly emptied by my thirsty clanmates. But I guess I'll save that story for a later time I'll just say that everyone was very delighted by the present. Please send my regards to the grogmakers.

Ah yes "oo" words So I took it as a challenge to see how many of these words I could shove into a story and here is the result. I hope you all enjoy

The Magical Shampoo

Long ago, in a town called Waterloo, there was quite a large zoo. In said zoo lived many animals but the most famous were quite an odd pair, Kazoo the kangaroo and his pet cockatoo Moo. One day, Moo started to notice that her feathers weren’t as shiny as they were before. Bothered by this, the kangaroo decided that they needed to do something. Days went and neither had any ideas of what could be done. Overhearing the problem, the wise old cockapoo called them over. He told both Kazoo and Moo of the old legend of the magical shampoo that could make any hair, fur and feathers feel like new again. After hearing this both Moo and Kazoo decided to head out to find the shampoo.
First they were told to go into the large bamboo forest and find the cave Voodoo. Entering the forest, both were afraid of what type of animals they would meet up with. Moo acting more like a chicken at the moment than a cockatoo had jumped into Kazoo’s pouch and went as far down as possible. Left alone to find the shampoo Kazoo entered the forest. The bamboo was so thick that Kazoo had to use his large feet to push it down so he could continue on. Once they were deep within the forest, Kazoo realized that although the old cockapoo told them that cave Voodoo was in this forest, he had not told them how to reach it.
After sitting for a while, Kazoo decided to head west. Hopping along, Kazoo landed on a rather large branch and fell over. Feeling this Moo flew out of the pouch squawking and screaming as she was unsure about what was going on. Trying to stop the hullabaloo she was making about all this, Kazoo fell a second time into a puddle of goo. Disgusted, Kazoo quickly got up trying to remove the goo as quickly as possible. While using his paws to remove it, he noticed that the scent of this goo was rather pleasant and that the places that the goo had been on made his fur shiny and soft. Moo had noticed this too. They both knew that this must be the magical shampoo and seeing that it continued on in the westward direction, they followed it.
Once they reached the end of the trail, they saw a rather large cave. Above read in big bold letters Cave Voodoo. Kazoo and Moo both had no idea how to get into the cave as a large stone lay in front. Trying to push it with all their might they could not move it. Suddenly etched in the stone, Moo noticed it said "play the didgeridoo". Looking around she saw a old looking didgeridoo. She chirped loudly at Kazoo and then pointed to the didgeridoo. Kazoo picked it up and blowing as hard as he could let out a long note. The stone slid out of the way allowing them access.
As they entered the cave they noticed how unique a cave it really was. While outside there was a jungle, cave Voodoo was even warmer even though it looked like an igloo. Moo felt cold and kept sneezing (achoo) so she jumped into the pouch once more while Kazoo continued on. Walking for quite some time, Kazoo came upon a large lake. Looking around Kazoo saw several skidoos but knew they could not use those to cross the lake. Looking more closely at them he noticed that one appeared different. It was a seadoo. Surely they could use this to cross the lake. Jumping aboard they began to cross the lake. This task was not as easy at it seemed as the very famous ghosts of Voodoo cave came out to scare them. Boo the ghosts would say and then they would laugh. Kazoo realized these were friendly ghosts and asked if they knew where the magical shampoo was. Simultaneously, the ghost turned their heads to one side and pointed to the left where a red light was coming from. Kazoo steered the seadoo to the red light.
Once reaching the the shore they saw a little blue cuckoo shining a bright red flashlight. Not wanting to stop for what seemed to be a crazy bird they ventured forward toward the end of the cave. As they neared the end they could see much better a blue light shining upon an object. To their shock they had indeed found the magical shampoo. Kazoo decided not to bother waking Moo and reached for the bottle. But it was no use. The bottle was a hologram. Now worried Kazoo decided to go back to talk to the cuckoo. Asking the cuckoo what was with the shampoo she only kept laughing. She then began to tell Kazoo about her silly switcheroo. The shampoo was a hologram and the real one was near by. She agreed to give it to them on one condition, they had to guess her tattoo? She mentioned that it was her name as well and if they had bothered to stop in the first place she would have told them. Not having any idea of what her name was they decided to ask for a hint. She mentioned that her name rhymed with booboo. Going through many different words from peek-a-boo to yahoo, Kazoo felt as if he had gone through all the possibilities. Getting frustrated, he began to shout more words hoping that maybe he'd say the right one. Hearing the commotion Moo came out and started to make a scene. Boohoo she cried and the cuckoo began to laugh again for her name indeed was Boohoo. Giggling she flew off and came back with the bottle of magical shampoo. As she flew away she only had one thing to say “Remember dear friends its quite taboo to enter cave Voodoo and not ask the name of the friendly cuckoo.” Not really knowing how to take this, they went on their merry way, back to the zoo. Moo was quite content as now her feathers shone like new.
